<body>
    <div class="wrapper">

        <!-- NAVIGATION -->

        <div class="left-box article">
            <img src="~/images/logo.png" alt="">
            <p>Graduating from the halls of the University Of Western Sydney in late 2011.</p>
            <ul>
                @foreach (Menu item in Model.Menus)
                {

                <li>
                    @{
                        if (item.ActionName.Equals(""))
                        {
                            <a href="#">@item.Name</a>

                        }
                        else
                        {
                            <a class="btn btn-outline-primary" role="button" asp-action="@item.ActionName"  asp-controller="@item.ControllerName">@item.Name</a>
                            
                        }
                        
                    }


                </li>

                }
                <li> <a class="btn btn-warning" role="button" asp-action="Login" asp-controller="Home">Log out</a></li>

            </ul>
           


        </div>

        <!-- Middle Box -->
        <!-- Orta hisse -->

        <section id="main">

            <div class="middleBox">
                <h1>News and Stories</h1>
                <p>
                    There's a lot of material out there about writing great headlines. Hey, getting someone to click on your article is a critical part of your blogging strategy. But what about writing introductions?

                    Compelling readers to actually read the article is an art form in and of itself -- and if you don't do it well, then you're denying yourself potential promoters, subscribers, leads, and even paying customers.
                </p>


                <!-- ITEM 1 -->

                <div class="boxItem">
                    @foreach (Article article in Model.Articles)
                    {
                        <h2>@article.Name</h2>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <i class="fas fa-comments"></i>@article.PublicDate
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <a href="">
                                    <i class="fas fa-comments"></i>@article.Category
                                </a>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <a href="">
                                    <i class="fas fa-comments"></i>3 Commets
                                </a>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        <img src="@article.Image" alt="">
                        <p>
                            @article.Description
                        </p>
                        <button type="submit" asp-action="FullArticle" asp-controller="Home" class="btn btn-light">READ MORE →</button>
                        <br />
                    }
                </div>

